<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-s4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>S4</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        S4 provides a formal approach to functional OOP. The underlying ideas
        are similar to S3 (the topic of <xref ref="ch-s3"/>), but implementation
        is much stricter and makes use of specialised functions for creating
        classes (<c>setClass()</c>), generics (<c>setGeneric()</c>), and
        methods (<c>setMethod()</c>). Additionally, S4 provides both multiple
        inheritance (i.e. a class can have multiple parents) and multiple
        dispatch (i.e. method dispatch can use the class of multiple arguments).
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-s4-classes">
      <title>Classes</title>

      <p>
        Unlike S3, S4 classes have a formal definition. To define an S4 class,
        you call <c>setClass()</c> with the class name and a definition of its
        fields (called <em>slots</em>):
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
setClass("Person", 
  representation(
    name = "character", 
    age = "numeric"
  )
)
        </input>
      </program>
    </section>

  </chapter>
